    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA235-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu varaivu nīṭa vāṟṟāḷāṅ kālattut tōḻi varaivu malintatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante rejoiced in marriage at a time when she was unable to bear it when the marriage was delayed.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA235">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            uravuttirai poruta piṇarpaṭu taṭavumuta</l>
<l>            laravu vāyā muḷḷilait tāḻai</l>
<l>            poṉṉēr tātiṟ puṉṉaiyoṭu kamaḻum</l>
<l>            palpūṅ kāṉaṟ pakaṟkuṟi vantunam</l>
<l>            meykaviṉ citaiyap peyarntaṉa ṉāyiṉuṅ </l>
<l>            kuṉṟiṟ ṟōṉṟuṅ kuvavumaṇa lēṟik</l>
<l>            kaṇṭaṉam varukañ ceṉmō tōḻi</l>
<l>            taṇṭā rakalam vaṇṭimir pūtap</l>
<l>            paṭumaṇik kalimā kaṭaii</l>
<l>            neṭunīrc cērppaṉ varūu māṟē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Even if he has come to the sign by day in the many-flowered</l>
<l rend="indent">seashore grove, where</l>
<l rend="indent2">the Tāḻai trees with thorny leaves are not surpassed by snakes<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">aravu vāyā</term> is a problem, and it does not become less so by adopting the better attested variant, <term xml:lang="ta">aravu vāḷ vāyā</term>. T.V.G. wants to read <term xml:lang="ta">vāyā</term> as a word of comparison and <term xml:lang="ta">aravu-vāḷ</term> as a single word for "saw". This has the look of an adhoc solution. One possibility with <term xml:lang="ta">aravu</term>, however, is that the Tāḻai thorns are as sharp or even sharper than a snake’s tooth.</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent3">with broad bases roughened as they are beaten by strong waves,</l>
<l rend="indent2">give fragrance along with the Puṉṉai tree with gold-like pollen,</l>
<l rend="indent3">[and] has gone [back] so that the beauty of our body is wasted,</l>
<l>– up, friend, let us see<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kaṇṭaṉam varukam</term>: here again this strange double verb for where the p.a. seems to express direct temporal anteriority.</note> [and] come [back],</l>
<l rend="indent">mounting the sand in heaps that appear like hills:</l>
<l>	the route the man from the coast of long waters is coming,</l>
<l rend="indent">impelling the spirited horses with ringing bells,</l>
<l rend="indent2">while bees are humming [and] filling themselves on [his] chest</l>
<l rend="indent4">[bearing] a cool garland.</l>
    </lg>
      </div>
